Ford GoBike Data¶

by Georgios Pallas¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The Ford GoBike dataset contains trip data for bike users in the San Francisco Bay Area, for the years 2017 (from June) and 2018.

In [2]:
# import all packages and set plots to be embedded inline
import numpy as np

import seaborn as sb; sb.set()
import zipfile

%matplotlib inline

Load data, provided in the Ford GoBike webpage, for the years of 2017 and 2018: https://www.fordgobike.com/system-data

# 2018 monthly data - name list
ext_file = ['01', '02', '03', '04', '05', '06', 
            '07', '08', '09', '10', '11', '12']
In [5]:
# unzip all 2018 monthly files
for i in ext_file:
    with zipfile.ZipFile('Data/2018' + i + '-fordgobike-tripdata.csv.zip', 'r') as myzip:
        myzip.extractall('Data')
In [6]:
# gather all 2018 monthly files and append them in a list
list_temp = []
for i in ext_file:
    df_month = pd.read_csv('Data/2018' + i + '-fordgobike-tripdata.csv')    
    list_temp.append(df_month)
In [7]:
# concatenate all monthly datasets together
df_2018 = pd.concat(list_temp, ignore_index=True)

I merged data from 2017 and 2018 years together, since each type of observetional unit should form a table (tidiness) and it will help me in my analysis.

We can already see some issues in the data above. For example missing values (e.g. for member birth year) or datatype issues (e.g. for station id or bike id). Let's look more carefully into the data.

First, I can see some columns which, for now, I don't plan to use them in my analysis.

  • start_station_latitude
  • start_station_longitude
  • end_station_latitude
  • end_station_longitude

I will discuss this again later, since it depends on the research questions I will try to explore if I will keep or remove these columns.

There is no information regarding this station with the specific geographical information in the dataset. There different ways to handle these missing station information. I could look into other data, for example in 2019 data that are provided from the Ford GoBike webpage and see if there are information about the station. Another idea, is to remove these instances. It is 11771 instances, which should not affect our analysis since it is a small number compared to the size of the dataset. Or I can keep them as null values.

Since the dataset is quite big I will remove them later in the cleaning section.

I cheched at the map and the station names provided at the web page ( https://member.fordgobike.com/map/ ) to pick the most relevant street name.

Summary of data assessment¶

One tidiness issue that I fixed was the merging of the tables together, so that I have in one place the trip data for 2017 and 2018. However, there might also be other tidiness issues. For example, the station information can be gathered in a separate table. In my analysis I don't plan to use the latitude and longitude information and I will remove these columns. However, a separate table that keeps this information can be useful for a future analysis.

One can also create a new column, and name it e.g. trip id, which will be unique for each of the bike trips. Then it will be easier to keep data like station information, bike trip information, user information in separate tables and track all necessary information among the tables.

Quality issues that I will fix in the cleaning section:

  • Remove the stations that do not have and id and name.
  • Remove the columns I will not use in my analysis like latitude, longitude, bike share columns.
  • Fix station names, so that each name corresponds to one id.
  • Fix datatypes.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

In this dataset, there are more than 2,000,000 bike trip data records, in the San Francisco Bay Area, with 11 features: duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year and member_gender.

There are some numeric variables, like the duration of the trips or the years, datetime variables as well as string names and a categorical variable.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of my dataset are those related to predicting where and when there will be high demand for bikes, as well as the population characteristics/ behaviour of those using the bikes.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Information about the stations (ids or names) will help me to determine which are the stations with high demand for bikes. Moreover, information regarding, first, the day and time, and secondly, the month, will help me to identify when is the specific time that there will be high demand for bikes. Additonal, information regarding type of users (subscriber or customer) will help me to identify if there are differences in behaviour for these two groups. Lastly, duration of the trips will help me identify how much on average the bikes are used, for example because they might require servicing after a specific amount of usage or in order to see after how much time bikes become available.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Of the variables of interest we saw that, for the whole population, most trips happen during the rush hours and during the week days. The majority of the population in the dataset, most likely uses the bikes to/from work.

Also the number of trips for subscribers is much higher than that of customers, meaning that the majority of people using the bikes are subscribers.

Moreover, I noticed that the pick number of trips is in October with a decrease in the trips for the months November and December. I also plotted the number of trips for 2017 and 2018 together but also separatelly, in order to see if the drop in the numbers of trips is something that happened in both years.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were some birth year values that are erroneous, e.g. for people born before 1900, as well as birth year values for very old people beyond 87 years old , that might be erroneous. For the birth year I plotted the distributions of those born above 1950, thus exluding some outliers.

For the trip durations, the max value identified is almost 24 hours! For the duration, I have plotted the values below the 98th percentile, again exluding the outliers. Furthermore, since the duration is in seconds I also plotted the duration in minutes to make the outcome more clear.

Finally, the bikes with high id numbers have been used mostly the last month of 2018. That might be explained if these are the newest bikes that have been placed in the busiest stations.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Some interesting relationsips were shown in the bivariate exploration. We recall that, in the single-variable exploration, there were more bike trips during the week days and during the rush hours. By adding the user type dimension in the charts (subscriber or customer) we were able to distinguish the two. Subscribers, which are the majority of the users in the dataset, are indeed use their bikes mostly in the week days and rush hours. Customers on the other hand, are mostly use the bikes in the weekends and almost equally throughout the day with a pick in the evening. That is an indicator that customers are not regular users and they are most likely visitors to the city.

With the bivariate exploration, we were able to see that customers are on average spend almost double the amount of time on a bike trip than subscribers. That can be explained if the customers are mostly visitors to the city and use the bikes in their leisure time. Subscribers on the other hand are mostly use their bikes during the week days and rush hours, that is most likely to/from work, so they probably care more about arriving at their destination fast.

Finally, the 10 busiest stations by number of bike trips for subscribers and customers were identified through the visual exploration. The analysis revealed the differences in distributions for the busiest stations for customers and subscribers. For customers, there were two stations that stant out compared to the rest of the stations. That might be explained, if these stations are close to destinations that are popular for the visitors of the city.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I have created a new variable decade, for users in their 20s to 60s. We could see in the exploration that the majority of the trips are for male users in their 30s followed by those in their 20s, while for females, the majority of trips are distributed equally for users in their 30s and 20s.

Finally, we could also see that males users spend on average less time per bike trip than female users, independently if they are subscribers or customers!
